This bill requires voters to provide paper proof of U.S. citizenship when registering to vote, such as a birth certificate, passport, or similar document, if their government-issued photo ID doesn’t confirm citizenship. States must verify citizenship using federal and state databases, notify applicants, and remove noncitizens from voter rolls. Registered voters flagged during checks must provide proof of citizenship to remain registered or have their vote counted. Election officials who do not enforce these rules may face penalties. All voters in federal elections must show a photo ID when voting in person, or include copies of both a government-issued photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship when voting by mail (absentee ballot). The ID must meet specific requirements, such as indicating U.S. citizenship and being issued by an approved authority. If a voter's citizenship is not verified, they can vote by casting a provisional ballot, which is counted only after citizenship is confirmed.

